Regression model VIII : Shrinkage

Read the chapter 11

Sometimes it can seem like you have too many predictors. If you use them all in your regression model, problems can arise. Explanation can be difficult due to collinearity as we saw before. Prediction performance can also be degraded by using too many predictors. But more predictors should mean more information. That should be helpful.

1 Ridge regression

Ridge regression makes the assumption that the regression coefficients (after normalization) should not be very large. Ridge regression is particularly effective when the model matrix is collinear and the usual least squares estimates of \(\beta\) appear to be unstable.

Suppose that the predictors have been centered by their means and scaled by their standard deviations and that the response has been centered. The ridge regression estimate chooses the \(\beta\) that minimizes:

\[(y-X\beta)^\top(y-X\beta) + \lambda\sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j^2\]

Ridge regression is an example of a penalized regression because of the presence of this term. The ridge regression estimates are given by:

\[\hat\beta = (X^\top X + \lambda I)^{-1} X^\top y\] The \(\lambda I\) introduces a “ridge” down the \(X^\top X\) matrix, hence the name of the method. An equivalent expression of the problem is that we choose b to minimize:

\[(y-X\beta)^\top(y-X\beta) \mbox{ subject to } \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j^2 \leq t^2 \]

The use of ridge regression can also be justified from a Bayesian perspective where a prior distribution on the parameters puts more weight on smaller values.

library(faraway)
## Warning: package 'faraway' was built under R version 3.6.2
data(meatspec, package="faraway")
trainmeat <- meatspec[1:172,]     # decomposition of data
testmeat <- meatspec[173:215,]
rmse <- function(x,y) sqrt(mean((x-y)^2))  # root MSE
require(MASS)
## Loading required package: MASS
## Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 3.6.2
rgmod <- lm.ridge(fat ~ ., trainmeat, lambda = seq(0, 5e-8, len=21))
matplot(rgmod$lambda, coef(rgmod), type="l", xlab=expression(lambda),ylab=expression(hat(beta)),col=1)
which.min(rgmod$GCV)    # estimated lambda minimizing GCV criterion
## 1.75e-08 
##        8
abline(v=1.75e-08)

ypred <- cbind(1,as.matrix(trainmeat[,-101])) %*% coef(rgmod)[8,]   # predicted value for training data
rmse(ypred, trainmeat$fat)
## [1] 0.8024395
ypred <- cbind(1,as.matrix(testmeat[,-101])) %*% coef(rgmod)[8,]    # predicted value for test data
rmse(ypred, testmeat$fat)
## [1] 4.101066
rmse(ypred[-13], testmeat$fat[-13])    # after removing a bad fit
## [1] 1.979462

\(\lambda = 0\) corresponds to least squares while we find that as \(\lambda \rightarrow \infty\) : \(\hat\beta \rightarrow 0\).

Ridge regression estimates of coefficients are biased. But, the resulting estimator gets more stable in the presence of multicollinearity. In that case, a large reduction in the variance may be obtained at the price of an increase in the bias.

2 LASSO (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator)

LASSO penalizes coefficient terms in the way of minimizing

\[(y-X\beta)^\top(y-X\beta) + \lambda\sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j|\]

and this is equivalent to minimizing

\[(y-X\beta)^\top(y-X\beta) \mbox{ subject to } \sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j| \leq t \] There is no explicit solution to this problem as in the ridge regression case although it can be found quite efficiently in the context of a more general method called least angle regression.

The important difference between lasso and ridge regression is on how we penalize the coefficient terms. For the LASSO, we use a \(L_1\) constraint and for the ridge, we use a \(L_2\) constraint. This difference causes different forms of solutions. See the figure below

The LASSO solutions tend to be sparse. It means that some of estimated coefficients are exactly zero. Therefore, by using LASSO, one may do estimation and variable selection in one shot.

For LASSO, the lars package is useful.

require(lars)
## Loading required package: lars
## Loaded lars 1.2
data(state)
statedata <- data.frame(state.x77,row.names=state.abb)
lmod <- lars(as.matrix(statedata[,-4]),statedata$Life)
plot(lmod)

We can see the solution path for this model.

set.seed(123)
cvlmod <- cv.lars(as.matrix(statedata[,-4]),statedata$Life)   # LASSO fitting with CV

We see the same selection result as the previous section. But, the value of coefficients were shrunk a bit.

Lasso is most useful for problems with much larger numbers of variables such as the ongoing spectroscopy example of this chapter. We compute the lasso fit for the training data:

trainy <- trainmeat$fat
trainx <- as.matrix(trainmeat[,-101])
lassomod <- lars(trainx,trainy)
set.seed(123)
cvout <- cv.lars(trainx,trainy)

cvout$index[which.min(cvout$cv)]
## [1] 0.01010101
testx <- as.matrix(testmeat[,-101])
predlars <- predict(lassomod,testx,s=0.0101,mode="fraction")
rmse(testmeat$fat, predlars$fit)
## [1] 2.132269
predlars <- predict(lassomod, s=0.0101, type="coef", mode="fraction")
plot(predlars$coef,type="h",ylab="Coefficient")

sum(predlars$coef != 0)
## [1] 20

The lasso is particularly useful when we believe the effects are sparse, i.e., that few of the predictors have an effect. For example, this arises in the analysis of gene expression data where we have good reason to believe that only a small number of genes have an influence on the quantity of interest.
